snippet.textDisplay: I'm kind of surprised that Epic didn't open their legal battles in the UK and EU, considering that their anti-monopoly laws are much stronger and more frequently enforced.  Maybe they thought that the US legal battle would be dragged out for much longer and wanted to have those legal proceedings started while the "easier" EU/ UK stuff was working its way through the courts?  Maybe setting a precedent in Europe will help with their case in the US.  Or maybe they don't think it's going as well in the states as they would have hoped and so Europe is a contingency plan.  If they can get Apple/ Google policies struck down in Europe, then the US case won't matter as much because it's going to piss off a lot of people if they hear that people can get Fortnite in Europe but not here.

snippet.textDisplay:
I actually kinda like the Optane, while a 32gig drive is a bit claustrophobic and it does run a bit on the wam side (1.8W standby power draw, wtf?) it actually is awesome to use as a swapdrive, in particular when paired with tmpfs (for non-linux folks, that is when you put your /tmp (the linux counterpart to "temporary files", but actually used a lot) in memory) it brings QLC up from "consumables" to "bi-annual replacement", and brings MLC to "usable" and brings SLC to "faster, since we have another drive to do the scattered writes on".

Optane also is kinda awesome in that it also suddenly gave you decent speed for more memory in case you've maxed out your RAM (my usecase needed about 4gig more than my motherboard allowed for - a 32gig stick of optane later and the system got a whole lot faster).

For people not into Optane - it basically is an extreme endurace drive with individually adressable bytes (so no annoying block re-writes) that is fast for random access, so if you deal with small files or non-sequential operations it is a whole lot faster than it seems. Or put another way: Optane is to SLC what SLC is to QLC (and yes, if you are one of those that the QLC is good enough for then the Optane makes no sense whatsoever, but if you are one of those that actually have need to pick SLC then Optane seems awesome, and if you run into the limitations of SLC then Optane replaces the "get another computer and use its RAM for swap and link it up over thunderbolt" method of getting stuff done (this latter case is probably why it only got killed in comsumer space))
